Convolutional Neural Networks, Nervana Neon¶

by:Reid Carper¶

Overview:¶

Convolutional Neural Networks (ConvNets or CNNs) are a category of Neural Networks that have proven very effective in areas such as image recognition and classification.¶

Today we will focus on the flow of how a CNN ingests data, learns, and makes predictions in a Nervana Neon environment.¶

-used to still find features even if the image is tilted, animal looking a different way, actor has a different color shirt on.. -rectified to make sure we keep the network non-linear -just like feature map on the input image, create a pooled feature map and a stride -find the MOST IMPORTANT the max() of the pixels in the image-produce 'pooled' features -another benefit is reducing the size of image again ~50-80% depending on stride size, preventing overfitting -explain overfitting
